\end{table}

\subsection{CUBRIC-provided derivatives}

In addition to raw BIDS data, CUBRIC distributes several pre-computed
derivatives:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Brain-extracted T1w images} via HD-BET for each session
  \item \textbf{Diffusion QC}: FSL \texttt{eddy\_qc} reports (motion
    parameters, outlier counts, CNR maps) for the multishell DWI
  \item \textbf{Structural and functional QC}: MRIQC reports for T1w,
    T2w, and BOLD data
  \item \textbf{MEG--MRI coregistrations}: T1w images transformed to
    CTF MEG coordinate space (Cardiff GitLab)
  \item \textbf{Phenotype data}: age, sex, ethnicity, anthropometrics
    (weight, height, waist/hip, blood pressure), alcohol and smoking
    status (\texttt{participants.tsv})
  \item \textbf{Cognitive and behavioural data}: trait questionnaires
    and task performance (\texttt{phenotype/} directory)
\end{itemize}

\noindent The processing reported here extends these CUBRIC derivatives
with quantitative tissue property maps (T1, BPF, T2*, g-ratio),
advanced subcortical segmentations (thalamic nuclei, hippocampal
subfields, hypothalamic subunits), perfusion quantification (CBF,
CMRO$_2$), and cross-modal validation analyses.

% ============================================================================
\section{Methods: Quantitative Structural Processing}
% ============================================================================

\subsection{FreeSurfer recon-all + advanced segmentations}

Standard cortical reconstruction was performed with FreeSurfer~8.2.0
(\texttt{recon-all} with T2-weighted pial refinement from ses-03).
Additional segmentations:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{SAMSEG}~\citep{Puonti2016samseg}: joint T1w+T2w Bayesian
        segmentation, providing tissue probability maps and intracranial volume.
  \item \textbf{SynthSeg}~\citep{Billot2023synthseg}: contrast-invariant DL
        segmentation applied to T1w from ses-02, 03, 04, 05 for cross-session
        volumetric consistency.
  \item \textbf{Hypothalamic subunits}: DL segmentation (Billot et al.\ 2020).
  \item \textbf{Thalamic nuclei}: FreeSurfer atlas-based segmentation with
        optional DTI enhancement.
  \item \textbf{Hippocampal subfields + amygdala nuclei}: with T2w for
        improved subfield boundaries.
\end{itemize}

% --- Figure: T1w orthographic ---
<<fig-t1w, fig.cap="Structural T1w (ses-03) for sub-08033. The T1-weighted image provides the anatomical reference for all cross-session registrations and serves as input for FreeSurfer cortical reconstruction, tissue segmentation (FAST/SAMSEG), and BEM forward model generation for MEG/EEG source localisation.", fig.height=3>>=
t1w_path <- file.path(wand_root, subject, "ses-03/anat",
                       paste0(subject, "_ses-03_T1w.nii.gz"))
ortho_view(t1w_path, "ses-03 T1w")
@

\subsection{T1w/T2w myelin ratio}

The T1w/T2w ratio~\citep{Glasser2011myelin} was computed after rigid-body
registration of the gradient-corrected T2w to T1w (FLIRT 6-DOF), SynthStrip
skull stripping, and voxelwise division. The ratio was projected to the
cortical mid-surface (\texttt{mri\_vol2surf}, 0.2--0.8 cortical depth).

<<fig-myelin, fig.cap="T1w/T2w myelin ratio (ses-03). This ratio serves as a widely-used proxy for cortical myelination, indexing the hierarchical organisation of cortex from heavily myelinated primary sensory areas to lightly myelinated association cortex. WAND uniquely allows validation of this proxy against ground-truth QMT bound pool fraction (Fig.~4) and multi-echo GRE R2* (Fig.~5).", fig.height=3>>=
myelin_path <- file.path(adv_dir, "myelin", "T1w_T2w_ratio.nii.gz")
ortho_view(myelin_path, "T1w/T2w Myelin Ratio")
@

\subsection{VFA T1 mapping (DESPOT1)}

Quantitative T1 was estimated from the ses-02 SPGR variable flip angle
data (8 flip angles: 2--18\textdegree, $\text{TR}_\text{exc}$~=~4\,ms)
using the linearised DESPOT1 method~\citep{Deoni2003despot}:
%
\begin{equation}
  \frac{S}{\sin\alpha} = E_1 \frac{S}{\tan\alpha} + M_0(1-E_1),
  \qquad E_1 = e^{-\text{TR}/T_1}
\end{equation}

<<fig-t1map, fig.cap="Quantitative T1 map from ses-02 SPGR variable flip angle data (DESPOT1). Quantitative T1 reflects tissue water content and macromolecular environment: white matter (short T1, dark) is distinguished from grey matter (longer T1, bright). This map serves as a required input for the QMT two-pool model and provides an independent measure of tissue composition alongside the T1w/T2w ratio.", fig.height=3>>=
t1map_path <- file.path(qmri_dir, "ses-02", "T1map.nii.gz")
if (file.exists(t1map_path)) {
  ortho_view(t1map_path, "VFA T1 Map (s)")
} else {
  plot.new(); text(0.5, 0.5, "T1 map not yet computed")
}
@

\subsection{QMT bound pool fraction}

Quantitative magnetization transfer was fitted from 11 MT-on volumes
(3 MT flip angles $\times$ multiple offset frequencies: 1--56\,kHz) plus
one MT-off reference, using a two-pool Ramani model~\citep{Ramani2002qmt}
with super-Lorentzian lineshape for the bound pool. The bound pool
fraction (BPF) provides a direct measure of macromolecular (myelin)
content~\citep{Sled2001qmt}.

<<fig-bpf, fig.cap="QMT bound pool fraction (ses-02, QUIT Ramani model with super-Lorentzian lineshape). BPF directly measures macromolecular (myelin) content via the restricted proton pool, providing the ground-truth measurement against which the T1w/T2w myelin proxy is validated. Median BPF = 0.10, consistent with healthy white matter. Combined with AxCaliber axon diameter, BPF yields the g-ratio and thence per-tract conduction velocity via the Hursh--Rushton relationship.", fig.height=3>>=
# Prefer QUIT output over Python fit
quit_bpf <- file.path(qmri_dir, "ses-02", "quit", "QMT_QMT_f_b.nii.gz")
py_bpf   <- file.path(qmri_dir, "ses-02", "QMT_bpf.nii.gz")
bpf_path <- if (file.exists(quit_bpf)) quit_bpf else py_bpf
if (file.exists(bpf_path)) {
  ortho_view(bpf_path, "QMT BPF (QUIT Ramani)", zlim = c(0.01, 0.20))
} else {
  plot.new(); text(0.5, 0.5, "QMT BPF not available")
}
@

\subsection{Multi-echo GRE: T2* and R2* mapping (ses-06)}

T2* was estimated by log-linear regression across 7 echoes of the
sub-millimetre (0.67\,mm) multi-echo GRE from ses-06. R2*~=~1/T2*
is sensitive to both iron and myelin content; combined with QSM
(from the phase data, not yet processed), iron and myelin contributions
can be separated.

<<fig-megre, fig.cap="Multi-echo GRE first echo magnitude (ses-06, 0.67\\,mm isotropic). The sub-millimetre resolution enables cortical depth-resolved analysis via LAYNII or Nighres. The 7-echo magnitude data yields R2* maps sensitive to iron and myelin; the phase data (not yet processed) enables QSM for separating paramagnetic iron from diamagnetic myelin contributions --- critical for resolving the feedforward/feedback cortical hierarchy.", fig.height=3>>=
# Show first echo magnitude — actual brain anatomy at sub-mm resolution
megre1_path <- file.path(wand_root, subject, "ses-06/anat",
                          paste0(subject, "_ses-06_echo-01_part-mag_MEGRE.nii.gz"))
if (file.exists(megre1_path)) {
  ortho_view(megre1_path, "MEGRE Echo 1 (0.67 mm)")
} else {
  plot.new(); text(0.5, 0.5, "MEGRE echo-01 not found")
}
@

\subsection{MP2RAGE quantitative T1 (ses-06)}

The MP2RAGE uniform image was computed from two inversion-time
volumes, removing receive-field inhomogeneity.

<<fig-mp2rage, fig.cap="MP2RAGE uniform image (ses-06, 0.7\\,mm isotropic). The MP2RAGE sequence provides B1-corrected quantitative T1 at sub-millimetre resolution, complementing the ses-02 VFA T1 map. Cross-validation between two independent T1 measurements (VFA and MP2RAGE) from different sessions and scanners tests the stability of quantitative tissue property estimation.", fig.height=3>>=
mp2_path <- file.path(qmri_dir, "ses-06", "MP2RAGE_uniform.nii.gz")
if (file.exists(mp2_path)) {
  ortho_view(mp2_path, "MP2RAGE Uniform (ses-06)")
} else {
  plot.new(); text(0.5, 0.5, "MP2RAGE not found")
}
@

\subsection{Perfusion: CBF from pCASL}

Cerebral blood flow was quantified from pseudo-continuous ASL
(bolus~=~1.8\,s, PLD~=~2.0\,s, 110 volumes) using FSL
\texttt{oxford\_asl}~\citep{Alsop2015asl} with voxelwise M0 calibration,
motion correction, and partial-volume correction. The ASL white paper
single-compartment model~\citep{Alsop2015asl} gives:
%
\begin{equation}
  \text{CBF} = \frac{6000 \cdot \lambda \cdot (\overline{S}_{\text{ctrl}} - \overline{S}_{\text{label}})
    \cdot e^{\text{PLD}/T_{1b}}}
    {2 \cdot \alpha \cdot T_{1b} \cdot M_0 \cdot (1 - e^{-\tau/T_{1b}})}
    \quad [\text{ml}/100\text{g}/\text{min}]
\end{equation}
%
where $\lambda$~=~0.9\,ml/g is the blood--brain partition coefficient,
$\alpha$~=~0.85 the labelling efficiency, $\tau$~=~1.8\,s the bolus
duration, and $T_{1b}$ the subject-specific blood T1.

\paragraph{Blood T1 from inversion recovery.}
Subject-specific $T_{1b}$ was estimated from the Look-Locker acquisition
(128$\times$128$\times$1, 960 time points, TR~=~150\,ms). The signal
in a sagittal sinus ROI was fitted to:
%
\begin{equation}
  S(t) = A\bigl(1 - B\,e^{-t/T_1^*}\bigr),
  \qquad T_1 = T_1^* \cdot B
\end{equation}
%
where the Deichmann--Haase correction recovers true $T_1$ from the
apparent $T_1^*$ and the inversion efficiency $B$.

<<fig-cbf, fig.cap="Calibrated CBF map from pCASL (ses-03, ml/100g/min). Cerebral blood flow is the first of three independent perfusion measurements in WAND. Combined with OEF from TRUST and CaO$_2$ from haematocrit, CBF enters Fick's equation to yield CMRO$_2$ --- the metabolic demand signal that drives the Balloon--Windkessel hemodynamic model. GM mean = 113, WM mean = 24\\,ml/100g/min.", fig.height=3>>=
cbf_path <- file.path(perf_dir, "oxford_asl", "native_space", "perfusion_calib.nii.gz")
if (file.exists(cbf_path)) {
  ortho_view(cbf_path, "CBF (ml/100g/min)")
} else {
  cbf_alt <- file.path(perf_dir, "oxford_asl", "native_space", "perfusion.nii.gz")
  if (file.exists(cbf_alt)) {
    ortho_view(cbf_alt, "CBF (a.u.)")
  } else {
    plot.new(); text(0.5, 0.5, "CBF: oxford_asl processing")
  }
}
@

\subsection{TRUST: venous oxygenation}

T2 of venous blood in the sagittal sinus was estimated from the
TRUST acquisition~\citep{Lu2008trust} (24 volumes, 4 effective TEs
$\times$ 3 repeats $\times$ control/label). The control--label
difference signal in the sinus decays as:
%
\begin{equation}
  |\Delta S|(\text{eTE}) = S_0 \, e^{-\text{eTE}/T_2}
\end{equation}
%
Venous T2 is calibrated to oxygen saturation $Y$ via the
quadratic model~\citep{Lu2012bloodt2} at 3\,T:
%
\begin{equation}
  \frac{1}{T_2} = A + B(1-Y) + C(1-Y)^2
  \label{eq:t2y}
\end{equation}
%
with coefficients $A$~=~4.5, $B$~=~47.1, $C$~=~55.5\,s$^{-1}$
for Hct~=~0.42. Solving the quadratic for $Y$ gives SvO$_2$,
from which OEF follows.

\subsection{CMRO$_2$ via Fick's principle}

The three independent perfusion measurements combine via the
Fick equation to give the cerebral metabolic rate of oxygen consumption:
%
\begin{equation}
  \text{CMRO}_2 = \text{CBF} \times \text{OEF} \times C_aO_2
\end{equation}
%
where OEF~=~(SaO$_2$~$-$~SvO$_2$)/SaO$_2$ from TRUST and the
arterial oxygen content is:
%
\begin{equation}
  C_aO_2 = [\text{Hb}] \times 1.34 \times \text{SaO}_2
    \approx 8.8\;\mu\text{mol\,O}_2/\text{ml\,blood}
\end{equation}
%
for Hb~=~15\,g/dl and SaO$_2$~=~0.98. This hierarchy from global OEF
(TRUST) can be upgraded to regional OEF via quantitative
BOLD~\citep{He2007qbold} fitting of the 7-echo GRE (ses-06).

% ============================================================================
\section{vpjax: Differentiable Vascular Physiology}
% ============================================================================

The quantitative structural maps feed into \textbf{vpjax} (Virtual
Physiology in JAX), the vascular/metabolic complement to vbjax
(Virtual Brain in JAX). Where vbjax provides neural mass models, vpjax
provides the complete physiological forward chain from neural activity
to measurable haemodynamic signals:
%
\begin{equation}
  \underbrace{z(t)}_{\text{neural}} \;\xrightarrow{\text{CMRO}_2}\;
  \underbrace{f(t)}_{\text{CBF}} \;\xrightarrow{\text{Balloon}}\;
  \underbrace{v(t),\; q(t)}_{\text{volume, deoxy-Hb}} \;\xrightarrow{T_2^*}\;
  \underbrace{y(t)}_{\text{BOLD/ASL/qBOLD}}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Balloon--Windkessel hemodynamics}

The extended Riera~\citep{Riera2006neurovascular} neurovascular model
replaces the simplified Buxton hemodynamics with a full metabolic
intermediate chain:
%
\begin{align}
  \dot{s} &= z - \kappa\, s - \gamma\,(f - 1) \label{eq:bw_s}\\
  \dot{f} &= s \label{eq:bw_f}\\
  \tau\,\dot{v} &= f - v^{1/\alpha} \label{eq:bw_v}\\
  \tau\,\dot{q} &= f\,\frac{E(f,\,\text{OEF}_0)}{E_0} - \frac{q}{v}\,v^{1/\alpha}
    \label{eq:bw_q}
\end{align}
%
where $E(f, E_0) = 1 - (1-E_0)^{1/f}$ is the oxygen extraction fraction
under the Grubb assumption, $\alpha$ is the Grubb exponent, $\kappa$ is the
signal decay rate, $\gamma$ the autoregulatory feedback, and $\tau$ the
transit time.

\subsection{qBOLD: regional OEF from multi-echo GRE}

The key upgrade from global OEF (TRUST) to regional OEF uses the
quantitative BOLD model~\citep{He2007qbold}:
%
\begin{equation}
  S(\text{TE}) = S_0 \;\cdot\; \mathcal{F}(\text{OEF},\,\text{DBV},\,\text{TE})
    \;\cdot\; e^{-R_2 \cdot \text{TE}}
  \label{eq:qbold}
\end{equation}
%
where $\mathcal{F}$ models the intravoxel frequency distribution from
randomly oriented deoxygenated vessels. At short TE the signal is
dominated by $R_2$ (tissue T2); at long TE by $R_2'$ (reversible,
from deoxy-Hb). The difference $R_2' = R_2^* - R_2 \propto
\text{OEF} \times \text{DBV} \times B_0$. WAND's 7-echo GRE
(TE~=~5--35\,ms) is ideal for fitting this model.

\subsection{CMRO$_2$ hierarchy}

vpjax provides three levels of oxygen metabolism estimation:
%
\begin{table}[htbp]
\centering
\caption{CMRO$_2$ estimation hierarchy in vpjax.}
\label{tab:cmro2}
\begin{tabular}{llll}
\toprule
Level & OEF source & Spatial resolution & WAND data \\
\midrule
1. Global  & TRUST (sagittal sinus T2)   & Whole-brain average & ses-03 TRUST \\
2. Regional & qBOLD (7-echo GRE, ses-06) & Per-voxel           & ses-06 MEGRE \\
3. Dynamic  & Riera model (Eqs.~\ref{eq:bw_s}--\ref{eq:bw_q}) & Time-varying & MEG + fMRI \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Local linearization integration}

The Balloon--Windkessel equations (Eqs.~\ref{eq:bw_s}--\ref{eq:bw_q})
are stiff: the vascular response evolves on a $\sim$1\,s timescale while
neural dynamics operate at $\sim$1\,ms. Standard Euler or RK4 integration
requires impractically small time steps. vpjax uses the
\textbf{local linearization} (LL) method (Ozaki 1992, extended by Riera),
which analytically solves the linearised system at each step:
%
\begin{equation}
  \mathbf{x}(t+\Delta t) = e^{\mathbf{J}(\mathbf{x}_t)\,\Delta t}\,\mathbf{x}(t)
    + \mathbf{J}^{-1}\!\bigl(e^{\mathbf{J}\,\Delta t} - \mathbf{I}\bigr)\,\mathbf{f}_0
\end{equation}
%
where $\mathbf{J} = \partial\mathbf{f}/\partial\mathbf{x}$ is the Jacobian
evaluated at the current state. This permits large time steps ($\Delta t$
up to 10$\times$ Euler) while remaining stable, and is fully differentiable
via \texttt{jax.grad} through the matrix exponential, enabling gradient-based
fitting of hemodynamic parameters alongside neural mass parameters in a
single optimization.

\subsection{Every variable has a measurement}

The central claim is that WAND provides independent measurements for
every state variable and parameter in the neurovascular model:
%
\begin{table}[htbp]
\centering
\caption{Model variables and their independent measurements.}
\label{tab:variables}
\begin{tabular}{lll}
\toprule
Model variable & vpjax module & WAND measurement \\
\midrule
Neural activity $z(t)$      & vbjax               & MEG \\
Metabolic demand (CMRO$_2$) & \texttt{metabolism/} & pCASL $\times$ TRUST \\
Blood flow $f(t)$           & \texttt{hemodynamics/} & pCASL CBF \\
Oxygen extraction $E(t)$    & \texttt{metabolism/oef} & TRUST SvO$_2$ \\
BOLD signal                 & \texttt{hemodynamics/bold} & ses-03 fMRI \\
Vascular geometry           & \texttt{vascular/}   & Angiography \\
E/I balance ($J_I$, $J_\text{NMDA}$) & constraint & MRS GABA/Glu \\
Myelination (g-ratio)       & constraint           & QMT BPF \\
Conduction velocity         & constraint (sbi4dwi) & AxCaliber \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Meshless physics: from tissue geometry to field solutions}

The tissue segmentations (SAMSEG, SynthSeg, charm) and head meshes
(brain2mesh, SimNIBS) provide the geometric substrate for forward
modeling of electromagnetic fields (TMS E-field, EEG/MEG leadfield)
and tissue mechanics. Traditional FEM approaches require mesh
generation, which is fragile, slow, and non-differentiable. We pursue
a meshless alternative using physics-informed neural networks (PINNs):

\paragraph{Conductivity estimation.}
The static current equation governs current flow through heterogeneous
tissue:
%
\begin{equation}
  \nabla \cdot \bigl(\sigma(\mathbf{x})\,\nabla V(\mathbf{x})\bigr) = -I_s(\mathbf{x})
  \label{eq:poisson}
\end{equation}
%
where $\sigma(\mathbf{x})$ is the tissue conductivity tensor and
$V(\mathbf{x})$ the electric potential. In sbi4dwi, both $V$ and
$\sigma$ are parameterised as Equinox MLPs and jointly optimised by
minimising the PDE residual (Eq.~\ref{eq:poisson}), electrode data
mismatch, and a pseudo-CT conductivity prior from WAND's quantitative
MRI:
%
\begin{equation}
  \mathcal{L}_\text{EIT} = \underbrace{\|\nabla\cdot(\sigma_\theta\nabla V_\phi)\|^2}_{\text{PDE}}
    + \lambda_d \underbrace{\|V_\phi(\mathbf{x}_e) - V_\text{meas}\|^2}_{\text{data}}
    + \lambda_r \underbrace{\|\sigma_\theta - \sigma_\text{prior}\|^2}_{\text{prior}}
\end{equation}

This meshless approach is fully differentiable via
\texttt{jax.grad}, enabling end-to-end backpropagation from
sensor-level TMS/EEG predictions through the conductivity model to
tissue property maps --- connecting the tissue segmentation pipeline
directly to the electromagnetic forward model without mesh generation.

\paragraph{Connection to Living Matter Physics.}
The same PINN framework extends to brain biomechanics
\citep{Kuhl2024livingmatter}: tissue elasticity, viscoelasticity, and
growth can be modelled by replacing the Poisson equation with the
equilibrium equations of continuum mechanics, using the same meshless
neural network solver. WAND's quantitative MRI (T1, T2*, QMT) provides
tissue-specific material property priors, and MR elastography (if
acquired) would provide direct validation. The differentiable nature of
JAX enables coupling mechanical deformation fields with neural dynamics
--- for example, predicting how traumatic brain injury alters
connectome-level conduction delays.

% ============================================================================
\section{Relaxometry Signal Models}
% ============================================================================

Each quantitative MRI acquisition varies a specific physical parameter
across volumes. Figure~\ref{fig:relaxometry} shows the signal models
overlaid on the measured data from a representative white-matter ROI.

<<fig-relaxometry, fig.cap="Relaxometry signal models for each multi-volume qMRI acquisition. (a) SPGR VFA: signal vs flip angle with DESPOT1 T1 fit. (b) Multi-echo GRE: signal vs echo time with mono-exponential T2* fit. (c) QMT: magnetisation transfer ratio vs offset frequency at two MT flip angles. (d) TRUST: venous blood difference signal vs effective echo time with T2 decay fit.", fig.height=8, fig.width=7>>=
suppressMessages(library(RNifti))

par(mfrow = c(2, 2), mar = c(4.5, 4.5, 3, 1), bg = "white")

# ---- (a) SPGR VFA: signal vs flip angle ----
spgr_path <- file.path(wand_root, subject, "ses-02/anat",
                        paste0(subject, "_ses-02_acq-spgr_part-mag_VFA.nii.gz"))
if (file.exists(spgr_path)) {
  spgr <- readNifti(spgr_path)
  d <- dim(spgr)
  # WM ROI (central)
  cx <- d[1] %/% 2; cy <- d[2] %/% 2; cz <- d[3] %/% 2
  roi <- spgr[(cx-3):(cx+3), (cy-3):(cy+3), (cz-3):(cz+3), ]
  mean_sig <- apply(roi, 4, mean)
  se_sig   <- apply(roi, 4, sd) / sqrt(prod(dim(roi)[1:3]))

  fa_deg <- c(2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12, 14, 18)
  fa_rad <- fa_deg * pi / 180
  TR <- 0.004

  # Fit DESPOT1
  Y <- mean_sig / sin(fa_rad)
  X <- mean_sig / tan(fa_rad)
  fit <- lm(Y ~ X)
  E1 <- coef(fit)[2]
  T1_fit <- -TR / log(E1)
  M0_fit <- coef(fit)[1] / (1 - E1)

  # Model curve
  fa_fine <- seq(1, 20, 0.5) * pi / 180
  S_model <- as.numeric(M0_fit) * sin(fa_fine) * (1 - E1) / (1 - E1 * cos(fa_fine))

  plot(fa_deg, mean_sig, pch = 19, col = "dodgerblue3",
       xlab = expression("Flip angle (" * degree * ")"),
       ylab = "Signal (a.u.)",
       main = "(a) SPGR Variable Flip Angle",
       ylim = c(0, max(mean_sig) * 1.2))
  arrows(fa_deg, mean_sig - se_sig, fa_deg, mean_sig + se_sig,
         angle = 90, code = 3, length = 0.05, col = "dodgerblue3")
  lines(fa_fine * 180 / pi, S_model, col = "firebrick", lwd = 2)
  legend("topright",
         legend = c("Data (WM ROI)",
                    bquote("DESPOT1: T1 =" ~ .(round(T1_fit * 1000)) ~ "ms")),
         pch = c(19, NA), lty = c(NA, 1), lwd = c(NA, 2),
         col = c("dodgerblue3", "firebrick"), cex = 0.8)
} else {
  plot.new(); text(0.5, 0.5, "SPGR data not found")
}

# ---- (b) Multi-echo GRE: signal vs TE ----
megre_dir <- file.path(wand_root, subject, "ses-06/anat")
echo_files <- list.files(megre_dir, pattern = "echo-.*_part-mag_MEGRE\\.nii\\.gz$",
                          full.names = TRUE)
echo_files <- sort(echo_files)

if (length(echo_files) >= 3) {
  # Extract echo times from JSON
  TEs <- sapply(echo_files, function(f) {
    jf <- sub("\\.nii\\.gz$", ".json", f)
    if (file.exists(jf)) jsonlite::fromJSON(jf)$EchoTime else NA
  })
  TEs <- TEs * 1000  # to ms

  # Load central slice from each echo
  signals <- sapply(echo_files, function(f) {
    img <- readNifti(f)
    d <- dim(img)
    roi <- img[(d[1]%/%2-2):(d[1]%/%2+2),
               (d[2]%/%2-2):(d[2]%/%2+2),
               d[3]%/%2]
    mean(roi)
  })

  # Fit T2*: S = S0 * exp(-TE/T2*)
  if (all(!is.na(TEs))) {
    log_sig <- log(pmax(signals, 1))
    fit_t2 <- lm(log_sig ~ TEs)
    T2star <- -1 / coef(fit_t2)[2]
    S0 <- exp(coef(fit_t2)[1])

    te_fine <- seq(min(TEs), max(TEs), 0.5)
    S_model <- S0 * exp(-te_fine / T2star)

    plot(TEs, signals, pch = 19, col = "darkgreen",
         xlab = "Echo time (ms)", ylab = "Signal (a.u.)",
         main = "(b) Multi-echo GRE (7 echoes)",
         ylim = c(0, max(signals) * 1.2))
    lines(te_fine, S_model, col = "firebrick", lwd = 2)
    legend("topright",
           legend = c("Data (WM ROI)",
                      bquote("Fit: T2* =" ~ .(round(T2star, 1)) ~ "ms")),
           pch = c(19, NA), lty = c(NA, 1), lwd = c(NA, 2),
           col = c("darkgreen", "firebrick"), cex = 0.8)
  }
} else {
  plot.new(); text(0.5, 0.5, "MEGRE data not found")
}

# ---- (c) QMT: MTR vs offset frequency ----
mtoff_path <- file.path(wand_root, subject, "ses-02/anat",
                         paste0(subject, "_ses-02_mt-off_part-mag_QMT.nii.gz"))
qmt_info <- data.frame(
  tag = c("flip-1_mt-1", "flip-1_mt-2",
          "flip-2_mt-1", "flip-2_mt-2", "flip-2_mt-3",
          "flip-2_mt-4", "flip-2_mt-5", "flip-2_mt-6",
          "flip-3_mt-1"),
  fa = c(332, 332, 628, 628, 628, 628, 628, 628, 333),
  offset = c(56360, 1000, 47180, 12060, 2750, 2770, 2790, 2890, 1000),
  stringsAsFactors = FALSE
)

if (file.exists(mtoff_path)) {
  mtoff <- readNifti(mtoff_path)
  d <- dim(mtoff)
  cx <- d[1] %/% 2; cy <- d[2] %/% 2; cz <- d[3] %/% 2
  s_off <- mean(mtoff[(cx-2):(cx+2), (cy-2):(cy+2), cz])

  mtrs <- numeric(nrow(qmt_info))
  for (i in seq_len(nrow(qmt_info))) {
    fname <- file.path(wand_root, subject, "ses-02/anat",
                        paste0(subject, "_ses-02_", qmt_info$tag[i],
                               "_part-mag_QMT.nii.gz"))
    if (file.exists(fname)) {
      img <- readNifti(fname)
      s_on <- mean(img[(cx-2):(cx+2), (cy-2):(cy+2), cz])
      mtrs[i] <- (s_off - s_on) / s_off
    }
  }

  # Plot MTR vs offset, colored by MT flip angle
  cols <- ifelse(qmt_info$fa > 500, "purple", "darkorange")
  plot(qmt_info$offset / 1000, mtrs, pch = 19, col = cols,
       xlab = "MT offset frequency (kHz)",
       ylab = "MTR = (S_off - S_on) / S_off",
       main = "(c) QMT: MTR vs Offset Frequency",
       log = "x", ylim = c(0, max(mtrs) * 1.2))
  legend("topright",
         legend = c(expression("FA"[MT] ~ "= 628" * degree),
                    expression("FA"[MT] ~ "= 332" * degree)),
         pch = 19, col = c("purple", "darkorange"), cex = 0.8)
  abline(h = 0, lty = 2, col = "gray50")
} else {
  plot.new(); text(0.5, 0.5, "QMT data not found")
}

# ---- (d) TRUST: difference signal vs eTE ----
trust_path <- file.path(wand_root, subject, "ses-03/perf",
                         paste0(subject, "_ses-03_acq-TRUST_cbf.nii.gz"))
if (file.exists(trust_path)) {
  trust <- readNifti(trust_path)
  d <- dim(trust)
  data2d <- trust[, , 1, ]  # (64, 64, 24)

  # Control-label pairs
  ctrl  <- data2d[, , seq(1, d[4], 2)]
  label <- data2d[, , seq(2, d[4], 2)]
  diff  <- abs(ctrl - label)

  eTEs <- c(0, 40, 80, 160)  # ms (nominal)
  n_eTEs <- length(eTEs)
  n_pairs <- d[4] %/% 2
  n_reps <- n_pairs %/% n_eTEs

  # Average per eTE
  diff_avg <- array(0, dim = c(d[1], d[2], n_eTEs))
  for (i in seq_len(n_eTEs)) {
    idx <- seq(i, n_pairs, n_eTEs)
    diff_avg[, , i] <- apply(diff[, , idx, drop = FALSE], c(1, 2), mean)
  }

  # Sinus ROI (top 5% at eTE=0)
  ete0 <- diff_avg[, , 1]
  thr <- quantile(ete0[ete0 > 0], 0.92)
  roi <- ete0 > thr
  roi_sig <- sapply(seq_len(n_eTEs), function(i) mean(diff_avg[, , i][roi]))

  # Fit T2
  ok <- roi_sig > 0
  if (sum(ok) >= 3) {
    fit_t2 <- nls(y ~ S0 * exp(-x / T2),
                  data = data.frame(x = eTEs[ok], y = roi_sig[ok]),
                  start = list(S0 = roi_sig[1], T2 = 60),
                  control = nls.control(maxiter = 200))
    T2_fit <- coef(fit_t2)["T2"]
    S0_fit <- coef(fit_t2)["S0"]

    ete_fine <- seq(0, 180, 2)
    S_model <- S0_fit * exp(-ete_fine / T2_fit)

    plot(eTEs, roi_sig, pch = 19, col = "tomato",
         xlab = "Effective echo time (ms)",
         ylab = expression("|" * Delta * "S| (ctrl - label)"),
         main = "(d) TRUST: Venous Blood T2",
         ylim = c(0, max(roi_sig) * 1.3))
    lines(ete_fine, S_model, col = "firebrick", lwd = 2)
    legend("topright",
           legend = c("Sinus ROI",
                      bquote("Fit: T2 =" ~ .(round(T2_fit)) ~ "ms")),
           pch = c(19, NA), lty = c(NA, 1), lwd = c(NA, 2),
           col = c("tomato", "firebrick"), cex = 0.8)
  }
} else {
  plot.new(); text(0.5, 0.5, "TRUST data not found")
}
@

% ============================================================================
\section{Results}
% ============================================================================

\subsection{Cross-session volumetrics (SynthSeg)}

<<tab-synthseg, results='asis'>>=
key_structs <- c("left cerebral white matter", "right cerebral white matter",
                 "left cerebral cortex", "right cerebral cortex",
                 "left hippocampus", "right hippocampus",
                 "left thalamus", "right thalamus")

sessions <- c("ses-02", "ses-03", "ses-04", "ses-05")
combined <- data.frame(Structure = key_structs, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

for (ses in sessions) {
  csv <- file.path(adv_dir, "synthseg", paste0(ses, "_volumes.csv"))
  if (file.exists(csv)) {
    df <- read.csv(csv, check.names = FALSE)
    cols <- tolower(names(df)[-1])
    vals <- as.numeric(df[1, -1])
    names(vals) <- cols
    combined[[ses]] <- round(vals[key_structs], 0)
  } else {
    combined[[ses]] <- NA
  }
}

cat("\\begin{table}[htbp]\n\\centering\n")
cat("\\caption{Cross-session volumetrics (SynthSeg, mm$^3$).}\n")
cat("\\label{tab:synthseg}\n")
cat("\\begin{tabular}{l", rep("r", length(sessions)), "}\n\\toprule\n", sep="")
cat("Structure & ", paste(sessions, collapse=" & "), "\\\\\n\\midrule\n")
for (i in seq_len(nrow(combined))) {
  vals <- paste(format(combined[i, -1], big.mark = ","), collapse = " & ")
  cat(combined$Structure[i], " & ", vals, "\\\\\n")
}
cat("\\bottomrule\n\\end{tabular}\n\\end{table}\n")
@

\subsection{SAMSEG tissue volumes}

<<tab-samseg, results='asis'>>=
samseg_csv <- file.path(adv_dir, "samseg", "samseg.csv")
if (file.exists(samseg_csv)) {
  samseg <- read.csv(samseg_csv, check.names = FALSE)
  # Format: ROI, volume_mm3, volume_ICV_x1000
  samseg <- samseg[order(-samseg$volume_mm3), ]
  # Skip Unknown and Intra-Cranial
  samseg <- samseg[!(samseg$ROI %in% c("Unknown", "Intra-Cranial")), ]
  top <- head(samseg, 12)
  esc <- function(x) gsub("_", "\\\\_", x)  # escape underscores
  cat("\\begin{table}[htbp]\n\\centering\n")
  cat("\\caption{SAMSEG tissue volumes (T1w+T2w joint segmentation).}\n")
  cat("\\label{tab:samseg}\n")
  cat("\\begin{tabular}{lr}\n\\toprule\n")
  cat("Structure & Volume (mm$^3$) \\\\\n\\midrule\n")
  for (i in seq_len(nrow(top))) {
    cat(esc(top$ROI[i]), " & ", format(round(top$volume_mm3[i]), big.mark=","), "\\\\\n")
  }
  cat("\\bottomrule\n\\end{tabular}\n\\end{table}\n")
} else {
  cat("SAMSEG results not yet available.\n")
}
@

\subsection{Hypothalamic subunits}

<<fig-hypo, fig.cap="Hypothalamic subunit segmentation overlaid on T1w. The hypothalamus regulates autonomic and neuroendocrine function; subunit volumes (anterior-inferior, posterior, tubular) provide structural markers of the autonomic nervous system that may predict individual differences in neurovascular coupling dynamics and TMS-evoked autonomic responses.", fig.height=3>>=
hypo_seg <- file.path(fs_dir, "mri", "hypothalamic_subunits_seg.v1.mgz")
t1_fs <- file.path(fs_dir, "mri", "T1.mgz")
if (file.exists(hypo_seg) && file.exists(t1_fs)) {
  suppressMessages(library(RNifti))
  seg <- readNifti(hypo_seg)
  t1  <- readNifti(t1_fs)
  d <- dim(t1)
  # Find slice with most hypothalamic voxels
  seg_sum <- apply(seg > 0, 3, sum)
  best_z <- which.max(seg_sum)
  ax_t1  <- t1[, , best_z]
  ax_seg <- seg[, , best_z]

  par(mfrow = c(1, 2), mar = c(0.5, 0.5, 2, 0.5), bg = "black")
  zlim_t1 <- quantile(ax_t1[ax_t1 > 0], c(0.01, 0.99), na.rm = TRUE)
  ax_t1[ax_t1 < zlim_t1[1]] <- zlim_t1[1]
  ax_t1[ax_t1 > zlim_t1[2]] <- zlim_t1[2]
  image(ax_t1, col = gray.colors(256), axes = FALSE, asp = 1)
  # Overlay segmentation
  seg_mask <- ax_seg > 0
  if (any(seg_mask)) {
    overlay <- ax_t1
    overlay[seg_mask] <- zlim_t1[2] * 1.2
    image(overlay, col = gray.colors(256), axes = FALSE, asp = 1)
    image(ifelse(ax_seg > 0, ax_seg, NA), col = rainbow(12, alpha = 0.6),
          axes = FALSE, asp = 1, add = TRUE)
  }
  mtext("Hypothalamic Subunits", side = 3, line = -1.5, outer = TRUE, col = "white", cex = 1.1)
  par(mfrow = c(1, 1), bg = "white")
} else {
  plot.new(); text(0.5, 0.5, "Hypothalamic seg not found")
}
@

<<tab-hypo, results='asis'>>=
hypo_csv <- file.path(fs_dir, "mri", "hypothalamic_subunits_volumes.v1.csv")
if (file.exists(hypo_csv)) {
  hypo <- read.csv(hypo_csv, check.names = FALSE)
  # Wide format: subject, left anterior-inferior, ..., whole left, whole right
  cols <- names(hypo)[-1]  # skip subject
  vals <- as.numeric(hypo[1, -1])
